ing force that holds the promise of universal peace, international law is a deeply politicized set of practices driven by the pursuit of particular interests and desires. The disputes so common in world politics over what law permits and what it forbids are, therefore, fights over the legitimating effect of legality.A reconsideration of the rule of law in world politics and its relationship to state power, How to Do Things with International Law examines how and why governments use and manipulate international law in foreign policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aInternational law. 0aRule of law. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Treaties.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAdobe.  aAdvisory opinion.  aAl-Qaeda.  aAmbiguity (law).  aAmendment.  aAnne-Marie Slaughter.  aAttempt.  aCodification (law).  aCoercion.  aCombatant.  aConstitutionalism.  aContract.  aCustom (law).  aDeclaration of war.  aDeliberation.  aDetermination.  aDissent.  aDue process.  aExplanation.  aFederal government of the United States.  aForeign policy.  aGeneva Conventions.  aGlobal governance.  aGlobal politics.  aGovernance.  aGovernment.  aGreat power.  aHumanitarian intervention.  aIdeology.  aInstitution.  aInternational Court of Justice.  aInternational human rights law.  aInternational humanitarian law.  aInternational law.  aInternational organization.  aInternational relations theory.  aInternational relations.  aInternational security.  aJurisdiction.  aJustifiable homicide.  aLaw of obligations.  aLaw of the United States.  aLaw of war.  aLawfare.  aLegal instrument.  aLegal personality.  aLegal positivism.  aLegalism (Chinese philosophy).  aLegality.  aLegalization.  aLegitimacy (political).  aLegitimation.  aLiberal inte